www.livemint.com/news/india/coronavirus-karnataka-shuts-down-schools-malls-theatres-for-a-week-11584099614638.html|website=livemint.com|access-date=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314044455/https://www.livemint.com/news/india/coronavirus-karnataka-shuts-down-schools-malls-theatres-for-a-week-11584099614638.html|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe Department of Primary and Secondary Education of Karnataka postponed the examinations for class 7 to 9 as a precautionary measure to avoid spread of [[coronavirus]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Class 7-9 exams postponed in Karnataka due to coronavirus|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/class-7-9-exams-postponed-in-karnataka-due-to-coronavirus-813925.html|newspaper=Deccan Herald|date=18 March 2020|access-date=16 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328095931/https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/class-7-9-exams-postponed-in-karnataka-due-to-coronavirus-813925.html|archive-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Karnataka]] has closed its borders with [[Kerala]] for vehicular traffic in the wake of six people testing positive for coronavirus in bordering [[Kasaragod district|Kasargod]] of [[Kerala]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Karnataka closes border with Kerala after 6 COVID-19 cases reported in Kasargod|url=https://www.theweek.in/news/india/2020/03/21/karnataka-closes-border-with-kerala-after-6-covid-19-cases-reported-in-kasargod.html|newspaper=The Week|date=21 March 2020|access-date=22 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322115014/https://www.theweek.in/news/india/2020/03/21/karnataka-closes-border-with-kerala-after-6-covid-19-cases-reported-in-kasargod.html|archive-date=22 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn Sunday 22 March, after the second meeting of the Task force formed to tackle the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]].The Government announced further restriction in the form of lock-down of 9 Districts until 31 March. All Non-Essential services in these districts were suspended. The nine Districts where [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] cases reported from included: [[Bangalore Rural district|Bengaluru Rural]], Bengaluru Urban, [[Chikkaballapura district|Chikkaballapura]], [[Dakshina Kannada]], [[Dharwad district|Dharwad]], [[Gulbarga district|Kalaburagi]], [[Mysore district|Mysuru]], [[Kodagu district|Kodagu]] and [[Belgaum district|Belagavi]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/state/top-karnataka-stories/coronavirus-nine-districts-including-bengaluru-under-lockdown-816473.html|title=Coronavirus: Nine districts, including Bengaluru, under lockdown|date=2020-03-22|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322195238/https://www.deccanherald.com/state/top-karnataka-stories/coronavirus-nine-districts-including-bengaluru-under-lockdown-816473.html|archive-date=22 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>  Further, to contain community transmission of the virus, Central Government took a major decision to Lockdown entire country for a period of 21 days beginning from 25 March.<ref>{{cite web |title=India lockdown for 21 days |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/what-is-coronavirus-lockdown/articleshow/74772624.cms |website=Times of India |access-date=25 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323155707/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/what-is-coronavirus-lockdown/articleshow/74772624.cms |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In line with Central Government's announcement, the State of Karnataka was also locked down. During the lock-down, all modes of public transport, commercial establishments were closed and any movement of people was restricted. However, shops and establishments providing essential services were allowed to be operational during the lock-down.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nThe Karnataka government has established an Toll-free Helpline number - 155214 for providing food to migrant labors in the state.<ref>{{Cite news|first=|url=https://karunadu.karnataka.gov.in/hfw/kannada/nCovDocs/28-03-2020(English).pdf|title=Media Bulletin|date=28 March 2020|work=karunadu.karnataka.gov.in|access-date=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328141934/https://karunadu.karnataka.gov.in/hfw/kannada/nCovDocs/28-03-2020(English).pdf|archive-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Lockdown 2.0===\nFurther, with states in favor of continuing the term of lockdown for another two weeks. During the fourth address to the nation concerning Coronavirus, Prime Minister Narendra Modi extended the lockdown till 3rd of May starting April 14th. However, based on the Centers\u2019 guidelines issued, The Chief Minister of Karnataka indicated the decision on relaxation would be taken on 20th of April after evaluating the extent of public conformity to the lockdown.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/karnataka/karnataka-for-stricter-lockdown-from-today-relaxation-of-norms-likely-after-april-20/article31343773.ece|title=Karnataka for stricter lockdown from today; relaxation of norms likely after April 20|last=|first=|date=15 April 2020|website=The Hindu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nFollowing up with the message of the extension of the lockdown. The Central Government announced a fresh set of guidelines to be observed by all States.\n\n* All places of social gatherings including religious conventions shall be barred.\n\n* Most of the Agricultural activities shall be exempted and will be allowed to be operated.\n\n* All Public work programs linked with employment of daily -wage-labours with social-distancing measures in place.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-52290761|title=Coronavirus lockdown guidelines: What has India changed under new rules?|last=|first=|date=15 April 2020|website=BBC News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Testing ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:85%\"\n|+ style=\"font-size:11pt;\" |{{nowrap|Details of Testing done in Karnataka}}\n! style=\"text-align:left    |Total Samples Received\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |21,636\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left    |Total Samples Tested\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |17,594\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left    |Total Samples Reported Positive\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |359\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left    |Samples Tested on: 17 April 2020\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |2,070\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left    |Samples Reported Positive on: 16 April 2020\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |44\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:right;\" |{{As of|2020|April|17}}<ref name=\"karunadu17apr\" />\n|}\n\nIndian scientists at [[Institute of Genomics and Integrative Biology]], using [[CRISPR gene editing]] tool developed a low cost paper-strip test for [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID 19]], which could give results in an hour. The estimated cost of the paper-strip test could be around {{INRConvert|500|}}. Currently, the kits are being tested for its accuracy and sensitivity. The team is awaiting approval from [[Indian Council of Medical Research]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/india-s-first-paper-strip-test-for-covid-19-csir-lab-makes-a-breakthrough-11585832200999.html|title=India's first paper-strip test for Covid-19, CSIR lab makes a breakthrough|last=Choudhary|first=Srishti|date=2 April 2020|website=LiveMint|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Quarantine===\nAs on 17 April, A total of '''13,313''' persons are under observation including international passengers(1752), Primary contacts(3669) and secondary contacts(7892).\n\n'''816''' patients in total are currently in isolation at Health facilities.<ref name=\"karunadu17apr\"/>\n\nThe summary of screening of all International traveller's, is as follows:\n\nTill 23 March 2020 - '''1,27,902''' passengers have been screened in Karnataka. The details of points of entry are as follows:\n\n* [[Kempegowda International Airport|Kempegowda International Airport, Bengaluru]] - 89,963 passengers cumulative.\n* [[Mangalore International Airport|Mangaluru International airport]] - 31,917 passengers cumulative.\n* [[New Mangalore Port|New Mangaluru Port]] and [[Karwar|Karwar Port]] - 6,022 passengers cumulative.<ref name=\"karunadu23\" />\n\n=== Counselling ===\nAs the patients diagnosed with COVID-19 were expected to stay in isolation for long durations at various health facilities, counselling sessions were provided to lift the morale of the patients. According to the Government of Karnataka, as of '''15''' '''April 2020''',  '''1,668''' such Mental health counseling sessions were conducted for the patients. In addition, '''38,206''' counseling sessions were conducted for migrants in the state.<ref name=\"karunadu16apr\" />\n\n==Cases ==\n{{Columns\n\n|col1='''Patient Number''':\n{{legend|#00FF00|Recovered (no detectable virus)}}\n{{legend|#FFFCBB|Clinically recovered}}\n{{legend|#D3D3D3|Under treatment/ Clearance not yet reported}}\n{{legend|#fbb|Deceased}}\n|col2='''Origin type''':\n*{{legend|#b4ffff|'''T''' \u2013 Blue: Overseas Travel - contracted virus at a location outside India (Level 1) or came in contact with a person with overseas travel history.  T2P (Travel to Person, Level 2) and P2P (Person to Person, Level 3) are also used^}}\n*{{legend|#c8ff96|'''TJ''' - Green: Attended Tablighi Jamaat event at Nizamuddin Markaz, or came in contact with an attendee - Cluster1}}\n*{{legend|#ffff96|'''DT''' - Yellow: Travel History of Delhi or contact of someone with Delhi travel history - Cluster2}}\n*{{legend|#ffdc8c|'''NP''' - Orange: Worked at Nanjanaguda Pharmaceutical company, or contact of a person who worked there - Cluster3}}\n*{{legend|#ffdcdc|'''U''' - Pink: Unknown origin or possible community spread}}\n<small>^'''Note:''' Darker shades may be used to indicate person-to-person spread within a trail or cluster.  For example, darker blue indicates Travel related person-to-person spread within family and close contacts</small>\n|col2width=55em\n|}}\n\n<div style=\"height:60em; overflow:auto\">\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width: 100%;\"\n\n! scope=\"col\" | Patient Number\n! scope=\"col\" | Date Announced\n! scope=\"col\" | Date Discharged/ Deceased\n! scope=\"col\" | Origin type\n! scope=\"col\" | Level\n! scope=\"col\" | Origin\n! scope=\"col\" | Location\n! scope=\"col\" | Sex-Age\n!Ref(s)\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;background: #FFFCBB;\"  | 1\n!scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\" | 9 Mar 2020\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\" | 27 Mar\n| style=\"text-align:center;background:#b4ffff;\"|'''T'''\n| style=\"text-align:center\"| 1\n| [[Austin|Austin, USA]] via [[Dubai]]\n| [[Bangalore|Bengaluru]]\n| M46\n| <ref name=\"karunadu9mar\">{{Cite web|url=https://karunadu.karnataka.gov.in/hfw/kannada/nCovDocs/09-03-2020(English).pdf|title=Media Bulletin|last=|first=|date=|website=Department of health and family welfare services,Karnataka|url-status=live|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;background: #FFFCBB;\" | 2\n! rowspan=\"3\" scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\" | 10 Mar 2020\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\" | 24 Mar\n| style=\"text-align:center;background:#78ffff;\"|'''T2P'''\n| style=\"text-align:center\"| 2\n| P#1 - Wife\n| [[Bangalore|Bengaluru]]\n| F47\n| rowspan=\"3\" | <ref name=\"karunadu10mar\">{{Cite web|url=https://karunadu.karnataka.gov.in/hfw/kannada/nCovDocs/10-03-2020(English).pdf|title=Media Bulletin|last=|first=|date=|website=Department of health and family welfare services,Karnataka|url-status=live|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;background: #FFFCBB;\" | 3\n! scope=\"row\" style=