{"title_page": "Kiasma", "text_new": "{{Infobox museum\n| name                = Kiasma\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| image               = Kiasmamodernartmuseum.JPG\n| caption             = The northern side of the Kiasma building\n| alt                 = \n| coordinates         = {{coord|60|10|18|N|24|56|13|E|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n| map_type  = Finland Helsinki (mainland)#Finland\n| map_caption = The location of the museum in [[Helsinki]]\n| former_name         = Museum of Contemporary Art ({{lang-fi|Nykytaiteen museo}})\n| established         = {{Start date|1990|df=y}} <small>(Museum of Contemporary Art)</small><br/>\n{{Start date|1998|df=y}} <small>(opening of Kiasma building)</small>\n| dissolved           = \n| location            = [[Helsinki]], [[Finland]]\n| type                = [[Art museum]]\n| accreditation       = \n| key_holdings        = \n| collections         = [[Contemporary art]]\n| collection_size     = \n| visitors            = 295,000 (2017)\n| founder             = \n| director            = Leevi Haapala\n| president           = \n| curator             = \n| owner               = [[Finnish National Gallery]]\n| publictransit       = \n| car_park            = \n| parking             = \n| network             = \n| website             = {{URL|http://www.kiasma.fi/en/}}\n| embedded            = \n}}\n\n'''Kiasma''' is a [[contemporary art]] [[museum]] located on [[Mannerheimintie]] in [[Helsinki]], [[Finland]]. Its name ''kiasma'', Finnish for [[Optic chiasm|chiasma]], alludes to the basic conceptual idea of its architect, [[Steven Holl]]. Kiasma is part of the [[Finnish National Gallery]], and it is responsible for the gallery's contemporary art collection. Its central goal is to showcase contemporary art and to strengthen its status.\n\n==History==\nThe contemporary art collection began as the Museum of Contemporary Art ({{lang-fi|Nykytaiteen museo}}) in 1990. In its earliest stages, the collection was housed in [[Ateneum]].\n\nAn [[architectural design competition]] to design a building for the contemporary arts museum was held in 1992. The competition was open to architects from the [[Nordic countries|Nordic]] and [[Baltic countries]], in addition to which four architects or studios from elsewhere were invited to participate, though they were obliged to submit their proposals anonymously: [[Steven Holl]] from the US, [[Alvaro Siza]] from Portugal, [[Coop Himmelblau]] from Austria, and [[Kazuo Shinohara]] from Japan.<ref>The Open Nordic/Baltic Design Competition for the Museum of Contemporary Art, Helsinki. ''Architectural Competitions in Finland'', 5/1993.</ref> The competition results were announced in 1993, and the winning proposal, titled ''Chiasma'' by Steven Holl, was selected from the 516 submitted entries. The design of the building, Finnishized as \"Kiasma\", underwent slight modification during the design process, but nevertheless was regarded as controversial; for instance its close proximity to the equestrian statue of Finnish President [[Carl Gustaf Emil Mannerheim]].<ref>G. Griffiths, \"Steven Holl and His Critics\", ''Ptah'', 1/2006.</ref> Construction work began in 1996, and the museum opened in May 1998.<ref name=\"kiasma_story\"/>\n\nThe museum attracted 160,000\u2013180,000 visitors per year in 2011\u20132013.<ref>{{cite book|title=Annual Report 2013|publisher=Finnish National Gallery|url=http://www.suomenkansallisgalleria.fi/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/VTM_annual_report_2013_web.pdf|accessdate=29 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170529205713/http://www.suomenkansallisgalleria.fi/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/VTM_annual_report_2013_web.pdf|archive-date=29 May 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nKiasma was closed for repairs in September 2014 and reopened in March 2015.<ref name=\"kiasma_story\">{{cite web|title=The story of Kiasma|url=http://www.kiasma.fi/en/kiasma/story-of-kiasma/|publisher=Kiasma|accessdate=29 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Kiasma Archive: 2015|url=https://kiasma.fi/arkisto/?cat=24&lang=en/|publisher=Kiasma|accessdate=15 May 2018}}</ref> In 2016, Kiasma attracted over 310,000 visitors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kansallisgalleria.fi/en/tietoa-kansallisgalleriasta/vuosikertomukset/|title=Annual Reports \u2022  Finnish National Gallery|website=www.kansallisgalleria.fi|language=en-US|access-date=2018-06-14}}</ref>\n\n== The collection ==\nThe collections include works by around 8,000 artists,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kiasma.fi/en/collections/|title=Kiasma - Kiasma Collections|website=kiasma.fi|language=en-US|access-date=2018-06-14}}</ref> including\nAhonen, Reetta,  Aiha, Martti, Aken, Jan van Andersson, Anders Gustaf, [[Antonio Rotta]], Baron, Bernard, Baumgartner, Stig, [[Cornelis Bega]], [[Nicolas Berchem]], [[Honor\u00e9 Daumier]], [[Karel Dujardin]], Nunzio Gulino, Torger  Enckell,  Aarne  J\u00e4ms\u00e4, Ismo Kajander, Raimo Kanerva, and Risto Laakkonen.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Finnish National Gallery]]\n** [[Ateneum]]\n** [[Sinebrychoff Art Museum]]\n* [[EMMA \u2013 Espoo Museum of Modern Art]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Nancy Marmer, \"Holl's Kiasma Debuts in Helsinki,\" ''Art in America,'' October 1998, p.&nbsp;35.\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.kiasma.fi/en/}}\n\n{{Helsinki Cityscape}}\n\n[[Category:Infrastructure completed in 1998]]\n[[Category:Contemporary art galleries in Finland]]\n[[Category:Museums in Helsinki]]\n[[Category:Modern art museums]]\n[[Category:Steven Holl buildings]]\n[[Category:Art museums and galleries in Finland]]\n[[Category:1998 establishments in Finland]]\n[[Category:Art museums established in 1998]]\n[[Category:Kluuvi]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox museum\n| name                = Kiasma\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| image               = Kiasmamodernartmuseum.JPG\n| caption             = The northern side of the Kiasma building\n| alt                 = \n| coordinates         = {{coord|60|10|18|N|24|56|13|E|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n| map_type  = Finland Helsinki (mainland)#Finland\n| map_caption = The location of the museum in [[Helsinki]]\n| former_name         = Museum of Contemporary Art ({{lang-fi|Nykytaiteen museo}})\n| established         = {{Start date|1990|df=y}} <small>(Museum of Contemporary Art)</small><br/>\n{{Start date|1998|df=y}} <small>(opening of Kiasma building)</small>\n| dissolved           = \n| location            = [[Helsinki]], [[Finland]]\n| type                = [[Art museum]]\n| accreditation       = \n| key_holdings        = \n| collections         = [[Contemporary art]]\n| collection_size     = \n| visitors            = 295,000 (2017)\n| founder             = \n| director            = Leevi Haapala\n| president           = \n| curator             = \n| owner               = [[Finnish National Gallery]]\n| publictransit       = \n| car_park            = \n| parking             = \n| network             = \n| website             = {{URL|http://www.kiasma.fi/en/}}\n| embedded            = \n}}\n\n'''Kiasma''' is a [[contemporary art]] [[museum]] located on [[Mannerheimintie]] in [[Helsinki]], [[Finland]]. Its name ''kiasma'', Finnish for [[Optic chiasm|chiasma]], alludes to the basic conceptual idea of its architect, [[Steven Holl]]. Kiasma is part of the [[Finnish National Gallery]], and it is responsible for the gallery's contemporary art collection. Its central goal is to showcase contemporary art and to strengthen its status.\n\n==History==\nThe contemporary art collection began as the Museum of Contemporary Art ({{lang-fi|Nykytaiteen museo}}) in 1990. In its earliest stages, the collection was housed in [[Ateneum]].\n\nAn [[architectural design competition]] to design a building for the contemporary arts museum was held in 1992. The competition was open to architects from the [[Nordic countries|Nordic]] and [[Baltic countries]], in addition to which four architects or studios from elsewhere were invited to participate, though they were obliged to submit their proposals anonymously: [[Steven Holl]] from the USA, [[Alvaro Siza]] from Portugal, [[Coop Himmelblau]] from Austria, and [[Kazuo Shinohara]] from Japan.<ref>The Open Nordic/Baltic Design Competition for the Museum of Contemporary Art, Helsinki. ''Architectural Competitions in Finland'', 5/1993.</ref> The competition results were announced in 1993, and the winning proposal, titled ''Chiasma'' by Steven Holl, was selected from the 516 submitted entries. The design of the building, Finnishized as \"Kiasma\", underwent slight modification during the design process, but nevertheless was regarded as controversial; for instance its close proximity to the equestrian statue of Finnish President [[Carl Gustaf Emil Mannerheim]].<ref>G. Griffiths, \"Steven Holl and His Critics\", ''Ptah'', 1/2006.</ref> Construction work began in 1996, and the museum opened in May 1998.<ref name=\"kiasma_story\"/>\n\nThe museum attracted 160,000\u2013180,000 visitors per year in 2011\u20132013.<ref>{{cite book|title=Annual Report 2013|publisher=Finnish National Gallery|url=http://www.suomenkansallisgalleria.fi/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/VTM_annual_report_2013_web.pdf|accessdate=29 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170529205713/http://www.suomenkansallisgalleria.fi/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/VTM_annual_report_2013_web.pdf|archive-date=29 May 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nKiasma was closed for repairs in September 2014 and reopened in March 2015.<ref name=\"kiasma_story\">{{cite web|title=The story of Kiasma|url=http://www.kiasma.fi/en/kiasma/story-of-kiasma/|publisher=Kiasma|accessdate=29 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Kiasma Archive: 2015|url=https://kiasma.fi/arkisto/?cat=24&lang=en/|publisher=Kiasma|accessdate=15 May 2018}}</ref> In 2016, Kiasma attracted over 310,000 visitors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kansallisgalleria.fi/en/tietoa-kansallisgalleriasta/vuosikertomukset/|title=Annual Reports \u2022  Finnish National Gallery|website=www.kansallisgalleria.fi|language=en-US|access-date=2018-06-14}}</ref>\n\n== The collection ==\nThe collections include works by around 8,000 artists,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kiasma.fi/en/collections/|title=Kiasma - Kiasma Collections|website=kiasma.fi|language=en-US|access-date=2018-06-14}}</ref> including\nAhonen, Reetta,  Aiha, Martti, Aken, Jan van Andersson, Anders Gustaf, [[Antonio Rotta]], Baron, Bernard, Baumgartner, Stig, [[Cornelis Bega]], [[Nicolas Berchem]], [[Honor\u00e9 Daumier]], [[Karel Dujardin]], Nunzio Gulino, Torger  Enckell,  Aarne  J\u00e4ms\u00e4, Ismo Kajander, Raimo Kanerva, and Risto Laakkonen.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Finnish National Gallery]]\n** [[Ateneum]]\n** [[Sinebrychoff Art Museum]]\n* [[EMMA \u2013 Espoo Museum of Modern Art]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Nancy Marmer, \"Holl's Kiasma Debuts in Helsinki,\" ''Art in America,'' October 1998, p.&nbsp;35.\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.kiasma.fi/en/}}\n\n{{Helsinki Cityscape}}\n\n[[Category:Infrastructure completed in 1998]]\n[[Category:Contemporary art galleries in Finland]]\n[[Category:Museums in Helsinki]]\n[[Category:Modern art museums]]\n[[Category:Steven Holl buildings]]\n[[Category:Art museums and galleries in Finland]]\n[[Category:1998 establishments in Finland]]\n[[Category:Art museums established in 1998]]\n[[Category:Kluuvi]]\n", "name_user": "Majavah", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:clean up,typo(s) fixed: the USA \u2192 the US", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kiasma"}
{"title_page": "SEA-ME-WE-6", "text_new": "{{Infobox cable\n| cable_name             = SEA-ME-WE 6\n| cable_logo             =\n| cable_type             = Submarine Fibre-optic\n| State                  =\n| predecessor            = [[SEA-ME-WE 3#Sea-Me-We|SEA-ME-WE]], [[SEA-ME-WE 3#Sea-Me-We 2|SEA-ME-WE 2]], [[SEA-ME-WE 3]], [[SEA-ME-WE 4]], [[SEA-ME-WE 5]]\n| successor              =\n| construction_beginning =\n| construction_finished  =\n| first_traffic          =\n| design_capacity        = 12 Tbit/s<ref name=\"DailySun\">{{Cite web|author=Jahangir, Shamim|title=Bangladesh to link with 3rd submarine cable next June|url=https://www.daily-sun.com/post/456074/Bangladesh-to-link-with-3rd-submarine-cable-next-June|website=The Daily Sun|access-date=2020-04-17|date=January 22, 2020}}</ref>\n| lit_capacity           =\n| built_by               =\n| defunct                =\n| landings               =\n| area_served            = South East Asia, Middle East Asia, Western Europe\n| owner                  = Consortium\n| homepage               =\n| footnotes              =\n}}\n'''South East Asia\u2013Middle East\u2013Western Europe 6''' ('''SEA-ME-WE 6''') is a proposed [[optical fibre]] [[submarine communications cable]] system that would carry telecommunications between [[Southeast Asia]], the [[Middle East]], and [[Western Europe]]. It is estimated to cost between $65&nbsp;million and US$72&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"daily star\">{{cite web|author=Islam, Muhammad Zahidul |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/business/news/two-singapore-firms-show-interest-3rd-submarine-cable-1746682|title=Two Singapore firms show interest in 3rd submarine cable|website=The Daily Star|access-date=2020-04-17|date=May 21, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"capacitymedia\">{{cite web|url=https://www.capacitymedia.com/articles/3823000/bangladesh-to-build-third-subsea-cable|website=capacitymedia.com|title=Capacity Media|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Bangladesh Govt Decides for 3rd Submarine Cable |url=https://subtelforum.com/bangladesh-govt-decides-for-3rd-submarine-cable/|website= subtelforum.com |access-date=2020-04-17|date=2019-01-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Bangladesh to connect with 3rd submarine cable by 2021 |url=http://en.banglatribune.com/tech-and-gadget/news/26493/Bangladesh-to-connect-with-3rd-submarine-cable-by|website= banglatribune.com |access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Bangladesh Submarine Cable Company Limited (BSCCL)\n|url=http://www.bsccl.com/doc/up_file/Office%20Order_04032019_1551672729-33.pdf|website= www.bsccl.com |access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/business/government-decides-for-3rd-submarine-cable-connect-in-bangladesh-1688437|title=Govt to go for third submarine cable|date=2019-01-17|website=The Daily Star|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>  [[Bangladesh]], [[Singapore]], [[Malaysia]], [[Indonesia]], [[Thailand]], [[Sri Lanka]], [[India]], [[Pakistan]], [[Saudi Arabia]], [[Qatar]], [[Oman]], the [[UAE]], [[Djibouti]], [[Egypt]], [[Turkey]], [[Italy]], [[France]], [[Myanmar]] and [[Yemen]] are members of the SEA-ME-WE-6 Consortium.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Four Int\u2019l Firms in Race to Build Third Submarine Cable|url=https://subtelforum.com/four-intl-firms-in-race-to-build-third-submarine-cable/|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> It will run from Singapore to France and will have a bandwidth of 12 Tbps.<ref name=\"DailySun\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[SEA-ME-WE 3]]\n* [[SEA-ME-WE 4]]\n* [[SEA-ME-WE 5]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Submarine communications cables in the Indian Ocean]]\n\n[[Category:Submarine communications cables in the Arabian Sea]]\n[[Category:Submarine communications cables in the Indian Ocean]]\n[[Category:Submarine communications cables in the Mediterranean Sea]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox cable\n| cable_name             = SEA-ME-WE 6\n| cable_logo             = \n| cable_type             = Submarine Fibre-optic\n| State                  = \n| predecessor            = [[SEA-ME-WE 3#Sea-Me-We|SEA-ME-WE]], [[SEA-ME-WE 3#Sea-Me-We 2|SEA-ME-WE 2]], [[SEA-ME-WE 3]], [[SEA-ME-WE 4]], [[SEA-ME-WE 5]]\n| successor              = \n| construction_beginning = \n| construction_finished  =\n| first_traffic          = \n| design_capacity        = 12 Tbit/s<ref name=\"DailySun\">{{Cite web|author=Jahangir, Shamim|title=Bangladesh to link with 3rd submarine cable next June|url=https://www.daily-sun.com/post/456074/Bangladesh-to-link-with-3rd-submarine-cable-next-June|website=The Daily Sun|access-date=2020-04-17|date=January 22, 2020}}</ref>\n| lit_capacity           = \n| built_by               = \n| defunct                = \n| landings               = \n| area_served            = South East Asia, Middle East Asia, Western Europe\n| owner                  = Consortium\n| homepage               = \n| footnotes              = \n}}\n'''South East Asia\u2013Middle East\u2013Western Europe 6''' ('''SEA-ME-WE 6''') is a proposed [[optical fibre]] [[submarine communications cable]] system that would carry telecommunications between [[Southeast Asia]], the [[Middle East]], and [[Western Europe]]. It is estimated to cost between $65&nbsp;million and US$72&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"daily star\">{{cite web|author=Islam, Muhammad Zahidul |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/business/news/two-singapore-firms-show-interest-3rd-submarine-cable-1746682|title=Two Singapore firms show interest in 3rd submarine cable|website=The Daily Star|access-date=2020-04-17|date=May 21, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"capacitymedia\">{{cite web|url=https://www.capacitymedia.com/articles/3823000/bangladesh-to-build-third-subsea-cable|website=capacitymedia.com|title=Capacity Media|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Bangladesh Govt Decides for 3rd Submarine Cable |url=https://subtelforum.com/bangladesh-govt-decides-for-3rd-submarine-cable/|website= subtelforum.com |access-date=2020-04-17|date=2019-01-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Bangladesh to connect with 3rd submarine cable by 2021 |url=http://en.banglatribune.com/tech-and-gadget/news/26493/Bangladesh-to-connect-with-3rd-submarine-cable-by|website= banglatribune.com |access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Bangladesh Submarine Cable Company Limited (BSCCL)\n|url=http://www.bsccl.com/doc/up_file/Office%20Order_04032019_1551672729-33.pdf|website= www.bsccl.com |access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/business/government-decides-for-3rd-submarine-cable-connect-in-bangladesh-1688437|title=Govt to go for third submarine cable|date=2019-01-17|website=The Daily Star|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>  [[Bangladesh]], [[Singapore]], [[Malaysia]], [[Indonesia]], [[Thailand]], [[Sri Lanka]], [[India]], [[Pakistan]], [[Saudi Arabia]], [[Qatar]], [[Oman]], the [[UAE]], [[Djibouti]], [[Egypt]], [[Turkey]], [[Italy]], [[France]], [[Myanmar]] and [[Yemen]] are members of the SEA-ME-WE-6 Consortium.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Four Int\u2019l Firms in Race to Build Third Submarine Cable|url=https://subtelforum.com/four-intl-firms-in-race-to-build-third-submarine-cable/|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> It will run from Singapore to France and will have a bandwidth of 12 Tbps.<ref name=\"DailySun\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[SEA-ME-WE 3]]\n*[[SEA-ME-WE 4]]\n*[[SEA-ME-WE 5]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n[[Category:Submarine communications cables in the Indian Ocean]]\n\n[[Category:Submarine communications cables in the Arabian Sea]]\n[[Category:Submarine communications cables in the Indian Ocean]]\n[[Category:Submarine communications cables in the Mediterranean Sea]]\n", "name_user": "Sulfurboy", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleaned up usingAutoEd", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SEA-ME-WE-6"}
{"title_page": "Helge Jung", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n| honorific_prefix  = \n| name              = Helge Jung\n| honorific_suffix  = \n| image         = Helge Jung.jpg\n| image_size    = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| native_name       = \n| native_name_lang  = \n| birth_name    = Helge Victor Jung\n| nickname      = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1886|3|23|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Malm\u00f6]], Sweden\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1978|1|3|1886|3|23|df=y}}\n| death_place   = [[Stockholm]], Sweden\n| placeofburial = [[Djursholm]] cemetery\n| placeofburial_label = \n| placeofburial_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n| allegiance    = [[Sweden]]\n| branch        = [[Swedish Army]]\n| serviceyears  = 1906\u20131951\n| rank          = General\n| servicenumber = <!-- Do not use data from primary sources such as service records -->\n| unit          = \n| commands      = {{bulleted list |[[North Scanian Infantry Regiment]]|[[Life Regiment Grenadiers]]|[[Army Staff (Sweden)|Army Staff]]|[[General Staff Corps]]|[[2nd Army Division (Sweden)|II Army Division]]|[[Lower Norrland Military District|II Military District]]|[[Eastern Military District (Sweden)|IV Military District]]|[[Commandant General in Stockholm]]|[[Supreme Commander of the Swedish Armed Forces|Supreme Commander]]}}\n| battles       = \n| battles_label = \n| awards        =\n| memorials     =\n| spouse        = <!-- Add spouse if reliably sourced -->\n| relations     = [[Bengt Liljestrand]] (son-in-law)\n| laterwork     = \n| signature     = \n| signature_size =\n| signature_alt =\n| website       = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| module        = \n}}\n[[General (Sweden)|General]] '''Helge Victor Jung''' (23 March 1886 \u2013 3 January 1978) was a [[Swedish Army]] officer. He was the [[Supreme Commander of the Swedish Armed Forces]] from 1944 to 1951.\n\n==Career==\n\n===Military career===\nJung was born in [[Malm\u00f6]], Sweden, the son of the headmaster Victor Jung and his wife Maria (n\u00e9e Levan). He was commissioned into the [[Swedish Army]] as a second lieutenant in the South Scanian Infantry Regiment (I 25) in 1906 and was a cadet officer at the [[Military Academy Karlberg|Royal Military Academy]] from 1919 to 1922. Jung was a teacher of military history together with strategy at the [[Royal Swedish Army Staff College]] from 1926 to 1928. He was the head of the Military History Department of the [[General Staff (Sweden)|General Staff]] in 1928 and was the Head of Department in 1929.<ref name=\"Vem \u00e4r det (1932), p. 424\">{{cite book |date=1932 |title=Vem \u00e4r det: svensk biografisk handbok. 1933 |trans-title=Who is it: Swedish biographical handbook. 1933 |location=Stockholm |publisher=Norstedt |language=Swedish |url=http://runeberg.org/vemardet/1933/0424.html |page=424}}</ref> Jung became a major in the General Staff in 1928, lieutenant colonel in 1933 and became colonel and commanding officer of the [[North Scanian Infantry Regiment]] (I 6) in 1936.<ref name=\"Harnesk (1962), p. 665\">{{cite book |editor1-last=Harnesk |editor1-first=Paul |date=1962 |title=Vem \u00e4r vem? 1, Stor-Stockholm |trans-title=Who is who? 1, Greater Stockholm |edition=2nd |location=Stockholm |publisher=Vem \u00e4r vem |language=Swedish |url=http://runeberg.org/vemarvem/sthlm62/0689.html |page=665}}</ref>\n\nJung was chief of the Military Office of the Land Defense (''Lantf\u00f6rsvarets kommandoexpedition'') from 1936 to 1937, colonel and executive officer of the [[Life Regiment Grenadiers]] (I 3) in 1936 and colonel and chief of the [[Army Staff (Sweden)|Army Staff]] and the [[General Staff Corps]] from 1937 to 1940. He became major general of the army in 1938 and was commanding officer of the [[2nd Army Division (Sweden)|II Army Division]] from 1940 to 1942. Jung was then the military commander of the [[Lower Norrland Military District|II Military District]] in 1942 and commanding officer of the [[Eastern Military District (Sweden)|IV Military District]] and was the [[Commandant General in Stockholm]] in 1943. He was appointed lieutenant general in 1944 and general in 1944. Jung was the Supreme Commander from 1944 to 1951.<ref name=\"Harnesk (1962), p. 665\"/>\n\n===Other works===\nHe was the founder and editor of the ''Ny milit\u00e4r tidskrift'' (\"New Military Journal\") from 1927 to 1930. Jung participated in or was the leader of several research trips for archival studies and battleground studies in Eastern and Central Europe for the General Staff Gustav-Adolfs-verk from 1922 to 1930.<ref name=\"Vem \u00e4r det (1932), p. 424\"/> He was the Secretary of the Army in the 1930 Defence Commission and in the 1936 Defence Committee.<ref name=\"Harnesk (1962), p. 665\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Djursholm, Helge Jung.JPG|thumb|Jung's grave in [[Djursholm]] Cemetery.]]\n\nIn 1913 he married Ruth Wehtje (1893\u20131951), the daughter of the deputy district judge Ernst Wehtje and Mimmi Ahnfelt. In 1952 he married Dagmar Bager (1897\u20131955), the daughter of vice consul John Jeansson and Sigrid Maijstr\u00f6m. He was the father of Stig (born 1915), Karin (born 1917) and Elisabet (born 1919\u20131994).<ref name=\"Harnesk (1962), p. 665\"/> Jung died on 3 January 1978 and was buried in [[Djursholm]] cemetery.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://finngraven.webdoc.nu/(S(r3jbluewtbjbh4amn1h0ubmb))/DisplayInfo.aspx?id=2003453 |publisher=Finngraven.se |title=Helge Viktor Jung |access-date=25 May 2015 |language=Swedish }}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Opinion==\nHelge Jung was largely a composite nature. His personality had traits of cunning and tactical calculation, even cynicism, but at the same time there were also clear hint of idealism and unselfish work for the Swedish military strengthening.<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Art\u00e9us |editor1-first=Gunnar |title=Svenska officersprofiler under 1900-talet |trans-title=Swedish officer profiles during the 1900s |year=1996 |publisher=Milit\u00e4rh\u00f6gsk. |location=Stockholm |isbn=91-87072-19-X |page=272 |language=Swedish}}</ref>\n\n==Dates of rank==\n*1906 \u2013 [[Unterleutnant|''Underl\u00f6jtnant'']]\n*19?? \u2013 [[L\u00f6jtnant|Lieutenant]]\n*19?? \u2013 [[Kapten|Captain]]\n*1929 \u2013 [[Major (Sweden)|Major]]\n*1933 \u2013 [[\u00d6verstel\u00f6jtnant|Lieutenant Colonel]]\n*1936 \u2013 [[\u00d6verste|Colonel]]\n*1938 \u2013 [[Generalmajor (Sweden)|Major General]]\n*1944 \u2013 [[Generall\u00f6jtnant|Lieutenant General]]\n*1944 \u2013 [[General (Sweden)|General]]\n\n==Awards and decorations==\n\n===Swedish===\n*[[File:Order of the Seraphim - Ribbon bar.svg|50px]] {{flag|Sweden}} Knight and Commander of the [[Royal Order of the Seraphim|Orders of His Majesty the King]] (Order of the Seraphim) (31 March 1951)<ref>{{cite book |url=http://runeberg.org/statskal/1955/1275.html |title=Sveriges statskalender f\u00f6r \u00e5ret 1955 |year=1955 |publisher=Fritzes offentliga publikationer |location=Stockholm |language=Swedish |page=7}}</ref>\n*[[File:Order of the Seraphim - Ribbon bar.svg|50px]] {{flag|Sweden}} [[Royal Jubilee Commemorative Medals|King Gustaf V's Jubilee Commemorative Medal]] (1948)<ref name=\"Statkal55Gen\">{{cite book |url=http://runeberg.org/statskal/1955/0352.html |title=Sveriges statskalender f\u00f6r \u00e5ret 1955 |year=1955 |publisher=Fritzes offentliga publikationer |location=Stockholm |language=Swedish |page=352}}</ref>\n*[[File:Order of the Sword - Ribbon bar.svg|50px]] {{flag|Sweden}} Commander Grand Cross of the [[Order of the Sword]] (6 June 1944)<ref>{{cite book |url=http://runeberg.org/statskal/1945bih/0009.html |title=Sveriges statskalender f\u00f6r \u00e5ret 1945 |year=1945 |publisher=Fritzes offentliga publikationer |location=Uppsala |language=Swedish |page=9}}</ref>\n*[[File:Order of the Sword - Ribbon bar.svg|50px]] {{flag|Sweden}} Commander First Class of the [[Order of the Sword]] (6 June 1939)<ref>{{cite book |url=http://runeberg.org/statskal/1940bih/0011.html |title=Sveriges statskalender f\u00f6r skott\u00e5ret 1940 |year=1940 |publisher=Fritzes offentliga publikationer |location=Uppsala |language=Swedish |page=11}}</ref>\n*[[File:Order of the Sword - Ribbon bar.svg|50px]] {{flag|Sweden}} Knight First Class of the [[Order of the Sword]] (1927)<ref>{{cite book |url=http://runeberg.org/statskal/1931bih/0035.html |title=Sveriges statskalender f\u00f6r \u00e5ret 1931 |year=1931 |publisher=Fritzes offentliga publikationer |location=Uppsala |language=Swedish |page=35}}</ref>\n*[[File:Order of the Polar Star - Ribbon bar, pre 1975.svg|50px]] {{flag|Sweden}} Knight of the [[Order of the Polar Star]] (1933)<ref>{{cite book |url=http://runeberg.org/statskal/1945bih/0081.html |title=Sveriges statskalender f\u00f6r \u00e5ret 1945 |year=1945 |publisher=Fritzes offentliga publikationer |location=Uppsala |language=Swedish |page=81}}</ref>\n*[[File:Order of the Vasa - Ribbon bar.svg|50px]] {{flag|Sweden}} Knight First Class of the [[Order of Vasa]] (1932)<ref>{{cite book |url=http://runeberg.org/statskal/1955/1477.html |title=Sveriges statskalender f\u00f6r \u00e5ret 1955 |year=1955 |publisher=Fritzes offentliga publikationer |location=Stockholm |language=Swedish |page=209}}</ref>\n*{{flag|Sweden}} Gold Medal of the [[Swedish Red Cross]]\n*{{flag|Sweden}} Gold Medal of the Swedish Central Federation for Voluntary Military Training (''Centralf\u00f6rbundet for bef\u00e4lsutbildnings guldmedalj'')\n*{{flag|Sweden}} Gold Medal of the Swedish Civil Defence League (''Sveriges civilf\u00f6rsvarsf\u00f6rbunds guldmedalj'')\n*{{flag|Sweden}} Gold Medal of the National Federation of Swedish Women\u2019s Auxiliary Defence Services (''Riksf\u00f6rbundet Sveriges lottak\u00e5rers guldmedalj'')\n*{{flag|Sweden}} Gold Medal of Merit of the [[Home Guard (Sweden)|Home Guard]] (''Hemv\u00e4rnets f\u00f6rtj\u00e4nstmedalj i guld'')\n*{{flag|Sweden}} Gold Medal of the Stockholm Association for Volunteer Military Training (''Stockholms bef\u00e4ls(utbildnings)f\u00f6rbunds guldmedalj'')\n*{{flag|Sweden}} Gold Medal of the Southern Scanian Association for Volunteer Military Training (''S\u00f6dra sk\u00e5nska bef\u00e4ls(utbildnings)f\u00f6rbunds guldmedalj'')\n*{{flag|Sweden}} Badge of Honor of the Swedish Reserve Officers Association (''Svenska reservofficersf\u00f6reningens hederstecken'')\n*{{flag|Sweden}} Badge of Honor of the Danish Shooting, Gymnastics and Sports Associations (''Danska Skytte-, gymnastik-och idrottsf\u00f6reningars hederstecken'')\n\n===Foreign===\n*[[File:DNK Order of Danebrog Grand Cross BAR.png|50px]] {{flag|Denmark}} Grand Cross of the [[Order of the Dannebrog]] (between 1945 and 1947)<ref name=\"Statkal45\u00d6verbef\u00e4lhav\">{{cite book |url=http://runeberg.org/statskal/1945/0109.html |title=Sveriges statskalender f\u00f6r \u00e5ret 1945 |year=1945 |publisher=Fritzes offentliga publikationer |location=Uppsala |language=Swedish |page=109}}</ref><ref name=\"Statkal47\u00d6verbef\u00e4lhav\">{{cite book |url=http://runeberg.org/statskal/1947/0109.html |title=Sveriges statskalender f\u00f6r \u00e5ret 1947 |year=1947 |publisher=Fritzes offentliga publikationer |location=Uppsala |language=Swedish |page=109}}</ref>\n*[[File:DNK Order of Danebrog Commander BAR.png|50px]] {{flag|Denmark}} Commander Second Class of the [[Order of the Dannebrog]] (between 1935 and 1940)<ref name=\"Statskal35\">{{cite book |title=Sveriges statskalender f\u00f6r \u00e5ret 1935 |year=1935 |publisher=Fritzes offentliga publikationer |location=Uppsala |language=Swedish |page=246}}</ref><ref name=\"Statkal40Genstabk\">{{cite book |url=http://runeberg.org/statskal/1940/0272.html |title=Sveriges statskalender f\u00f6r skott\u00e5ret 1940 |year=1940 |publisher=Fritzes offentliga publikationer |location=Uppsala |language=Swedish |page=272}}</ref>\n*[[File:DNK Kong Christian den Tiendes frihedsmedaille ribbon bar.png|50px]] {{flag|Denmark}} [[King Christian X's Liberty Medal]]<ref name=\"Harnesk (1962), p. 665\"/>\n*[[File:FIN Order of the White Rose Grand Cross BAR.png|50px]] {{flag|Finland}} Commander Grand Cross of the [[Order of the White Rose of Finland]] (between 1947 and 1950)<ref name=\"Statkal47\u00d6verbef\u00e4lhav\"/><ref name=\"Statkal50\u00d6verbef\u00e4lhav\">{{cite book |url=http://runeberg.org/statskal/1950/0101.html |title=Sveriges statskalender f\u00f6r \u00e5ret 1950 |year=1950 |publisher=Fritzes offentliga publikationer |location=Stockholm |language=Swedish |page=101}}</ref>\n*[[File:FIN Order of the White Rose Commander BAR.png|50px]] {{flag|Finland}} Commander of the [[Order of the White Rose of Finland]] (between 1935 and 1940)<ref name=\"Statskal35\"/><ref name=\"Statkal40Genstabk\"/>\n*[[File:FIN Order of the White Rose Knight 1st Class BAR.png|50px]] {{flag|Finland}} Knight First Class of the [[Order of the White Rose of Finland]] (between 1931 and 1935)<ref name=\"Statskal35\"/><ref name=\"Statkal31Genstab\">{{cite book |url=http://runeberg.org/statskal/1931/0240.html |title=Sveriges statskalender f\u00f6r \u00e5ret 1931 |year=1931 |publisher=Fritzes offentliga publikationer |location=Uppsala |language=Swedish |page=240}}</ref>\n*[[File:St Olavs Orden storkors stripe.svg|50px]] {{flag|Norway}} Grand Cross of the [[Order of St. Olav]] (between 1945 and 1947)<ref name=\"Statkal45\u00d6verbef\u00e4lhav\"/><ref name=\"Statkal47\u00d6verbef\u00e4lhav\"/>\n*[[File:St Olavs Orden kommand\u00f8r stripe.svg|50px]] {{flag|Norway}} Commander of the [[Order of St. Olav]] (between 1935 and 1940)<ref name=\"Statskal35\"/><ref name=\"Statkal40Genstabk\"/>\n*[[File:LTU Order of the Lithuanian Grand Duke Gediminas - Commander's Grand Cross BAR.png|50px]] {{flag|Lithuania}} Commander Grand Cross of the [[Order of the Lithuanian Grand Duke Gediminas]] (between 1935 and 1940)<ref name=\"Statskal35\"/><ref name=\"Statkal40Genstabk\"/>\n*[[File:DEU Deutsche Adlerorden 1 BAR.svg|50px]] {{flag|Nazi Germany}} [[Order of 